2026-05-17 19:17:41 | DEBUG | strands_evaluation.instrumentation.agent_plugins | Model response #6 [role=assistant block=1 tool_use] execute_code({"code": "import pandas as pd\n\npath = DOWNLOAD_PATHS['s3://sana-kramabench/datagov/kramabench-environment-hard-9/files/wollaston_beach_datasheet.csv']\n# Read with no header, then inspect\ndf = pd.read_csv(path, header=None)\nprint('shape', df.shape)\nprint(df.head(10).to_string(index=False))\n\n# Find the row index where the actual header (Date,1-Day Rain...) appears\nfor i, row in df.iterrows():\n    if row[0] == 'Date':\n        header_idx = i\n        break\nprint('header_idx', header_idx)\n\ndf2 = pd.read_csv(path, header=header_idx)\nprint('df2 shape', df2.shape)\nprint(df2.columns.tolist())\nprint(df2.head().to_string(index=False))\n\n# Relevant years 2019-2023 inclusive. The Date column has month day year; convert\ndf2['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df2['Date'].str.replace('\"',''), errors='coerce')\nprint(df2['Date'].min(), df2['Date'].max())\n\n# Determine how 'meets swimming standards' is encoded. Look at Enterococcus columns names\nent_cols = [c for c in df2.columns if 'Enterococcus' in c]\nprint('enterococcus cols', ent_cols)\nprint(df2[ent_cols].head(10).to_string(index=False))\n\n# The Tag columns seem to hold '<' markers. We'll create a 'meets' rule: Enterococcus numeric <= 104? or tag '<'10 considered meet\n# But need to check beach standard: Usually EPA single sample Enterococcus limit is 104 cfu/100mL for marine waters.\n# We'll assume samples with numeric Enterococcus <= 104 meet swimming standard; also tags like '<' indicate below detection and meet.\n\n# Clean the Enterococcus columns to numeric: remove '<' and coerce\nfor c in ent_cols:\n    df2[c+'_num'] = df2[c].astype(str).str.replace('<','').str.strip()\n    df2[c+'_num'] = pd.to_numeric(df2[c+'_num'], errors='coerce')\n\n# For each row, if all sampled Enterococcus locations (there are 4) meet <=104 or are NaN? We should treat presence of any value >104 as NOT meet.\nnum_cols = [c+'_num' for c in ent_cols]\n\n# Filter years 2019-2023 inclusive\nmask_year = df2['Date'].dt.year.between(2019,2023)\ndf_period = df2[mask_year].copy()\nprint('rows in period', len(df_period))\nprint(df_period[['Date']+num_cols].head(20).to_string(index=False))\n\n# Compute meet per row: True if all present numeric values <=104 and any '<' tag implies numeric small and was converted; but NaN means missing sample -> we will ignore NaN in the \"all\" logic: require that any numeric value >104 exists -> fail; else pass\n\ndef meets(row):\n    vals = row[num_cols].dropna()\n    if len(vals)==0:\n        return False\n    return (vals<=104).all()\n\n\ndf_period['meets'] = df_period.apply(meets, axis=1)\nprint('meets counts', df_period['meets'].value_counts(dropna=False))\n\n# Percentage of days in period where meets True\npct = 100*df_period['meets'].sum()/len(df_period)\nprint('pct', pct)\n\n# Print counts by year\nbyyear = df_period.groupby(df_period['Date'].dt.year)['meets'].agg(['count','sum'])\nprint(byyear)\n\nprint('done')\n\n# Output pct for assistant\nprint(pct)"}) [toolUseId=call_NfwZKtf2fpDs9CuY6kBRsog5]
